04999nam a22005055i 9780228017141DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280171417 a10.1515/97802280171412doi  a(DE-B1597)658106  a(OCoLC)1394871726  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aUA602.R6bJ37 2023 7aHIS0271602bisacsh04a356/.109712231 aJarymowycz, Roman Johann, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe History of the Black Watch (Royal Highland Regiment) of Canada: Volume 2, 1939–1945 :bVolume 2: 1939–1945 /cRoman Johann Jarymowycz. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource :b115 illustrations, 18 maps, full colour  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tThe Royal Highlanders of Canada in the Second World War 1939–1945 -- tMobilization and Guarding Canals, 1 RHC Mobilized – August 1939 -- tRegimental Commanders, 1939–1944 Dieppe, Italy and UK -- tNormandy – The Battles for Verrières Ridge: July–August 1944 -- tNormandy – The Black Watch Assaults Verrières Ridge, 25 July 1944 -- tFrance, Holland and the Scheldt August to December 1944 -- tThe Last Year of War: January to May 1945 -- tNotes to Part 4 -- tIllustrations -- tMaps -- tAppendix -- tIndex to Volume II0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn three volumes spanning centuries, Lieutenant Colonel Roman Jarymowycz recounts the story of the Black Watch (Royal Highland Regiment) of Canada, the oldest Highland regiment in the country. He traces its history from the roots, when soldiers, settlers, and militia volunteers rallied to defend the southern borders of their adopted country against invasion from the United States. Drawing on diaries, letters, classified documents, and the regimental archive, Jarymowycz weaves the strands of a complex story into an epic narrative of a resolute collective of officers and men.Since its birth in 1862 as the 5th Battalion, Volunteer Militia Rifles of Canada, thousands of citizens have served in the unit. In addition to securing Canada’s borders, Black Watch soldiers have fought in the South African War, both world wars, and the Korean War. They have bolstered NATO operations and United Nations peacekeeping missions, and they provided aid to the civil power during the 1997 Quebec and Eastern Ontario ice storm disaster and the COVID-19 pandemic. The Montreal-based battalion continues to serve Canada in its traditional role as a reserve infantry unit, and to this day, Black Watch soldiers frequently deploy on dangerous missions abroad. In volume 2 we are offered the story of the bloody battlefields of the Second World War, when the Black Watch joined Commonwealth regiments to defeat the Axis Powers. After a quick mobilization in 1939 and a long wait in England, the Black Watch experienced a baptism by fire at Dieppe. Landing in Normandy after D-Day, the regiment fought in France, Belgium, the Netherlands, and Germany, its distinguished service earning numerous honours. As well as discussing these military engagements, Jarymowycz reveals the many difficulties with recruiting, training, recovering from devastating battles, communicating with higher command, and the quality and scarcity of reinforcements. This monumental history of Canada’s oldest Highland regiment is at once a record of Scottish heritage, a portrait of Montreal rising as an industrial giant, and an examination of the emergence of a military culture from the Western Front.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Military / Canada.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z9783